<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF76FADEFD02FA93" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" box="[151,738,1368,1395]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Size. Known adult size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F03FF94FE07FADEFDB5FA92" box="[486,597,1368,1395]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="cm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F03FF94FF26FAFAFC7FF81B" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26FAFAFB39F9E2" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Morphology. D VI + I,14; A I,12–13; P 20–21. Large goby with stout body, moderately long snout with moderately steep profile, thick lips. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. First dorsal fin higher than the second dorsal fin; first dorsal fin spines decreasing posteriorly, shaping a curved margin. Caudal fin rounded. Predorsal area and nape scaled. Scales small, visible on body and predorsal area as dense pattern.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26F98AFD3BF93B" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Live coloration. Body mostly mottled brown, with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FCFDF98AFD63F9AB" bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">large darker, squarish midlateral blotches, each one preceded and followed by a white patch</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FD74F9B6FD0CF9AA" box="[661,748,1584,1611]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Back with 4 broad dark transverse bands, the second and fourth the darkest, separated by 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE1DF9D2FD32F98F" bold="true" box="[508,722,1620,1646]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">thin white saddles</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FD00F9D2FCD4F98E" box="[737,820,1620,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FCA9F9D2FE8BF973" bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Lips mostly vermilion, with a white bar below eye, at angle of mouth</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FE9AF9FEFE2DF972" box="[379,461,1656,1683]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) (red color usually not detectable under natural light only). Membranes of both dorsal fins are highly variegated, mixing irregular patches of red, dark brown and white coloration. Rows of head sensory papillae well-visible and bicolored black and white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26F962FDCCF8C2" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Similar species. No similar species in the Mediterranean. However, with no artificial light, may be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F03FF94FF31F88EFE43F8C3" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[208,419,1800,1826]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paganellus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FF31F88EFE43F8C3" box="[208,419,1800,1826]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Gobius paganellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F03FF94FE29F88EFDC5F8C3" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[456,549,1800,1826]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE29F88EFDC5F8C3" box="[456,549,1800,1826]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">G. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26F8AAFC75F88B" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F03FF94FD75F8AAFD07F8A6" box="[660,743,1836,1863]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="m" value="20.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="1.0">1–40 m</quantity>
depth on inshore rocky habitats, sand with stones and boulders, and in seagrass meadows (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FDB7F8D6FD05F88A" author="Louisy, P." box="[598,741,1872,1899]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref60639" refString="Louisy, P. (2015) Europe and Mediterranean Marine Fish Identification Guide. 3 rd Edition. Eugen Ulmer Ed., Paris, 512 pp." type="book" year="2015">Louisy 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FD10F8D7FC68F88B" author="Patzner, R. A." box="[753,904,1872,1899]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref62855" refString="Patzner, R. A. (2021) Gobiidae. Available from: http: // www. patzner. sbg. ac. at / Gobiidae / GobiidaeSpecies. htm (accessed 1 October 2021)" type="url" year="2021">Patzner 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26F8F2FC7FF81B" blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Geographic distribution. Northeastern Atlantic, Mediterranean and Black Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FBB5F8F2FAC5F86F" author="Engin, S. &amp; Turan, D. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[1108,1317,1908,1935]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="87 - 88" refId="ref53866" refString="Engin, S., Turan, D. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2007) First record of the red-mouthed goby, Gobius cruentatus (Gobiidae), in the Black Sea. Cybium, 31, 87 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.26028 / cybium / 2007 - 311 - 012" type="journal article" year="2007">
Engin 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FB45F8F3FB39F86F" box="[1188,1241,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FAD5F8F2FF34F853" author="Vasil'eva, E. D." pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref65796" refString="Vasil'eva, E. D. (2007) Fish of the Black Sea. Key to marine, brackish-water, euryhaline, and anadromous species with color illustrations, collected by S. V. Bogorodsky. VNIRO Publishing, Moscow, 237 pp. [in Russian, with English abstract]" type="book" year="2007">Vasil’eva 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In the Atlantic, occurs from the counties of Cork and Kerry in Ireland to 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F03FF94FBE7F81FFB53F853" box="[1030,1203,1944,1971]" name="Western Sahara" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Western Sahara</collectingCountry>
(Miller 1986). In the Mediterranean, all along the northern coast, and along the southern coast in 
